          "body": "Read in canonical context, 2 Chronicles 31 stands as the Old Testament's most detailed template for translating a spiritual awakening into sustained institutional structures. Nehemiah 10-13 follows the same pattern: post-exilic revival leads immediately to signed pledges of tithe-giving, Sabbath observance, and priestly division restoration. Malachi's covenant lawsuit (Mal 3:6-12) exposes what happens when these structures decay — the tithes cease, the priests go unfed, the Levites abandon the temple for agricultural work. The New Testament church addresses the same structural necessity: Acts 6:1-7 appoints deacons specifically so that the apostles can 'devote themselves to prayer and to the ministry of the word' — the precise logic of 2 Chronicles 31:4. Paul's instructions on systematic giving (1 Cor 16:1-4; 2 Cor 8-9) and the support of those who teach (Gal 6:6; 1 Tim 5:17-18) carry the same covenantal architecture. The chapter's principle is permanent: when God's people organize their material resources in faithful obedience to His word, those who handle the word are freed to do so with full devotion, and the blessing overflows."
